-- `fip` now proves the third FP^2 property: bounded stack. A recursive call
-- that is not in tail position keeps one frame alive per element, so it is
-- rejected. `relay` is linear (each binding used exactly once, no duplication)
-- yet its self-call sits under `wrap`, so it is non-tail and fails the new rule.
-- Making the call a tail call, a tail under one constructor / addition, or
-- annotating it `fbip` are the ways out the diagnostic names.
fip fn wrap(x) = x

fip fn relay(x) = wrap(relay(x))
